That is unplayable! That went away like a leg spinner. It is on a length and around off, it pitches and moves away sharply. Buttler tries to defend but is beaten, by a long way though.
A huge appeal but not given! This is floated up outside off, it turns back in. Overton gets his pad out of the line of off and tries to defend but misses to get hit on it.
That stayed low but nicely played! This is on off, it stays very low. Buttler gets his bat down in time and works it through square leg for one.
Quicker and on middle, this is worked through square leg for one.
That lobs to short leg but it is off the pads. It lands around off and then turns back in. Overton looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.
Flatter and on off, Buttler goes right back and works it with the turn towards backward square leg for one.
Shorter and on middle, Overton works it through square leg and gets Buttler on strike.

The ball is being checked and it does not pass through the 8-ball gauge which means time for it be changed. Out come the boxes. One is chosen and on we go. Also, Nathan Lyon is brought back on. Change of ends for him.
A length ball outside off to end. Buttler lets it go. This is really been a watchful innings by Buttler.
Crisp drive! Very full and on off, Jos creams it but to mid off.
This is angled into the stumps, Jos defends it back towards the bowler.
Good length and outside off, it is left alone.
On the fuller side on off, Buttler punches it past the bowler. Bancroft the sub at mid off dives to his right and makes a good stop.
This is fuller and on off, it tails back in. Overton gets his front leg out of the way and works it down to fine leg for one.
Pat Cummins is back on now! He has four till now and been their best bowler in this innings. He would look to add to his wicket-tally.

Interesting thoughts from Michael Atherton on air. He observes that Starc has been more successful when he has hit the length, rather than going for the yorker. Examples can be seen from the Bairstow dismissals in both innings.
A leave to end as Starc bowls it outside off.
Well bowled! This is on a length and around middle, stays a touch low. Buttler does well to keep it out.
A couple! Fuller and on off, Buttler strokes it through cover-point for two.
A yorker outside off, Buttler jams it out to point.
Buttler pulls out as Starc was steaming in. The bowler needs to reload.
One more delivery outside off, Buttler does not fiddle with it.
Outside off, it is left alone.
A shorter delivery to end on middle, Overton works it to mid-wicket.
Nicely bowled! This is slower and it is  tossed up outside off, Overton lunges and tries to defend but it goes off the inner half wide of short leg.
Flatter and outside off, Overton goes back and keeps it out.
Another one is worked to the mid-wicket region.
Floats it up on off, it is kept out.
On middle, it is worked to mid-wicket.
Nathan Lyon is back into the attack! His figures so far 16-2-45-1.
Around off, defended back to the bowler.
Outside off, left alone.
Landed outside off, left alone.

This is edged but played with soft hands. Hence, goes down to ground. Full and outside off, swinging away, Craig looks to drive but the ball goes off the outside edge, onto the ground and towards second slip who misfields and allows a single.
That was on target as well. Full and just around off, stays low a touch, Overton gets down to keep it out.
Craig Overton walks in now, at number 8, replacing Bairstow, as Australia get into the bowlers. Or bowling all-rounders. Overton was the night watchman in the first innings.

OUT! LBW! Jonny Bairstow has to walk back. Starc strikes first ball after Drinks. How often do we see a wicket after the break! Beauty from him to wrap him in front of the stumps. Height was the only issue which could've had saved him but no, the Ball Tracker rolls in to show that the the ball is clipping the stumps.  It was pitched on a good length and came back in sharply. Bairstow wanted to work it down the leg side but was hit flush on the pads. A huge appeal follows and umpire Dharmasena agrees with the Aussies. Bairstow though sends it upstairs after having a look at Buttler at the non-striker's end but he has to walk back. Second time Starc gets him in his Test and the 8th overall - most by any bowler against Jonny.
Starc takes out Bairstow again! LBW this time! Or is it? Review time... hit on the knee roll... here comes Ball Tracker. Umpire's call!

DRINKS! Australia got the wicket of Joe Denly early in the first hour of the second session but since then Jonny Bairstow along with Jos Buttler have done well to add 45 runs between them. Apart from that one wicket, the Australian bowling has not been good as they have been either too short or too straight. What's in the store for the next hour in this extended session? Change of ends for Starc after Drinks.

Misfield! Labuschagne comes from around the wicket to land it in the rough. He ends up bowling a full toss which Jonny works it through mid-wicket. Head in the deep gets to the ball but misfields and an extra run is taken. Three in total.
A little too short, Buttler works it behind square on the leg side for one. These two are going along well here. Actually, it was an inside edge onto the pads and not right off the middle.
Loopy ball around the pads, it is worked to the man at mid on.
Flatter and outside off, Buttler lets it be.
On middle. JB keeps it out.
A full toss but Buttler misses out. He smashes it but straight back to the bowler.
Change of ends for Marnus Labuschagne.
This is wider outside off, it turns back in but not enough to make the batter play.
This is given a lot more air and the length is fuller around off. Bairstow defends it, off the front foot.
One more ball to which JB goes back and works it to short fine leg.
Loopy ball on off, JB flicks it with the turn to the leg side.
A little too straight, it is worked to the fielder at short fine leg.
Slower through the air outside off, Bairstow goes back and pushes it back to the bowler.
Travis Head is on now! Just the one over for Labuschagne.
Better! This is on a length and around off, Buttler is solid in defense.
Too short! Buttler guides it to point. Starc has been a touch short in this spell. He needs to get it up there.

Looking at Marnus Labuschagne, David Gower just remembers the era of the 70s and the 80s, while discussing with Michael Atherton. He recounts that while touring the country Down Under, almost every state had a leg spinner. As a batsman, you needed to adjust pretty quickly. Talk about that around 40 years later, there is hardly any leggie to talk about...
Slightly fuller than the last ball. Buttler pushes it to covers.
Short again, Buttler easily goes back and keeps it out.
Way too wide outside off, the batter need not play at those.
A little too short and a little too straight, Bairstow works it through mid-wicket for one.
A good nut to end! On middle, Buttler defends it outside the line. It goes off the inner half to the right of the bowler. Two good deliveries to end by ML.
Good line and length! It is landed on middle, it turns away. Buttler gets right behind the line and keeps it out.
Another one which is a touch short. Bairstow this time goes back and pushes it through covers for one.
Shorter again and on off, Buttler pushes it through covers for one.
Big turn there! Tosses this one up outside off, Buttler shoulders arms to it as it turns away.
Flatter and on off, Bairstow guides it through point and gets to the other end.
Marnus Labuschagne is on now!
Three to end the over! Easy for Bairstow. It is full and on the pads, Bairstow works it through mid-wicket. The sweeper runs to his left and stops it. Three taken.
Shorter in length and on middle, Bairstow stands tall and pushes it to mid on.
Better! This is angled into the stumps, JB keeps it out. Starc not getting the ball to do a lot till now.
Shorter but down the leg side, Bairstow looks to flick but misses. Paine dives to his left and takes it nicely.
Goes fuller this time but no swing visible. It is outside off, left alone.
Starts off with a short ball so does not give the ball much time to do its bit. Bairstow ducks under it.
Mitchell Starc is back on now! The other pacers did get the ball to reverse. Can he do so? If he can, he can be handy.
Another one which is very full, Buttler flicks it to mid on. 9 from the over.
FOUR! Lovely use of the wrists! Also, there is minimal risk in that shot as it was with the turn. On middle and it is fuller. Buttler whips it through mid-wicket and the ball races away to the fence.
Very full and on middle, this is worked through square leg for one.
Flatter and on off, Jonny defends it out.
FOUR! Too full and it is put away! Full and on off, Bairstow leans into it and strokes it down to the long off fence.
Quicker and on off, Bairstow flicks but can't get past short leg.
One more ball outside off, Buttler shoulders arms to this one.
A little too straight, it is worked wide of mid on for one.
This starts on off and it comes back in. Bairstow looks to defend but it goes off the inner half towards square leg.
Attacks the stumps once again, Bairstow is solid in defense.
One more on a length and around off, Bairstow goes back and keeps it out.
Back of a length on off, Jonny stands tall and pushes it to covers.
Halt in play as Paine needs to go to the washroom! He is done and he rushes onto the field now.
Floats it up and on off, Buttler goes back and keeps it onto the ground. He went back to a pretty full delivery there but that is how he has been playing Lyon throughout the series.
On middle, Buttler works it to short fine leg for no runs.
Very full outside off, Buttler defends it out.
Outside off, JB looks to play it late, it goes off the outer half towards short third man for one.
On off, Bairstow goes back and keeps it out.
Flatter and outside off, it spins back in again. Bairstow goes back and tries to defend but misses to get hit high on the pads.
Fuller ball but outside off, Buttler doesn't play at it.
Fuller ball this time, negotiated easily by Buttler.
Good leave that one as Buttler trusted the length. The ball pitches outside off and comes back in sharply. Buttler shoulders arms and watches it go over the stumps.
Another one angled into the batter. Another solid block from Buttler.
Good length ball which is angled into the batter, Buttler blocks it well.
Shortish ball on middle, tucked towards the leg side.
Josh Hazlewood into the attack now!
Amit The Mastermind - 'Dear Garry, please keep your lengths a bit fuller. With these short stuff, you are taking LBW out of contention totally.'
This lands on off but then turns back in. Buttler works it around the corner for one.
Changes the angle and bowls it from around the wicket. It is down the leg side, Paine fails to collect it and it goes down towards fine leg. A bye is taken.
One more single! This time Buttler goes right back and works it behind square for one.
A single now as Jonny works it through square leg and gets to the other end.
Nicely played! This is floated up outside off, Buttler gets his front leg to the pitch of the ball and then strokes it through covers for three. Just a mere push there.
On middle, Bairstow works it with the turn through mid-wicket and gets to the other end.
Another length ball on off to end the over. Buttler goes back and keeps it out.
Slightly fuller this time and it shapes back in. Buttler looks to defend but it goes off the inner half towards mid on.
That kept a bit low! On middle and it stays a touch low. Buttler looks to defend but it goes off the bottom part towards mid-wicket.
Good length delivery outside off, Buttler does not play at it.
A little too straight this time from wide of the crease. Jonny nudges it through backward square leg and gets to the other end.
Shorter in length and around off, Bairstow guides it behind point and takes two.
Down the leg side, it is left alone.
Another one which lands outside off and turns back in. Buttler looks to flick but misses to get hit high on the pads.
Down the leg side, Buttler lets it be.
Very full and on off, Buttler strokes it to mid off.
This is flatter again outside off, it turns back in. Buttler goes back and tries to defend but misses to get hit high on the pads.
Flatter and quicker on the pads, it is worked through square leg for one.
Beaten! A superb nut to finish the over. Pitched on middle on a length and shapes away to go past the outside edge.
FOUR BYES! Bumper but too high as Buttler ducks. Even Paine can't do much as it flies over him towards the fine leg fence.
On the pads this time, clipped towards square leg for a couple. It brings 100 up for England and it gets huge cheer from the English supporters.
Shortish ball outside off this time, Buttler shoulders arms.
EDGY FOUR! Goes slightly fuller around off, Buttler looks to push it towards the off side but the ball takes the outside edge and goes wide of the slip cordon to the third man fence.
Good length ball angled into the batter, Buttler hops and pushes it towards mid on.
Flighted ball outside off, it turns back in. Buttler tries to defend but it goes off the inner half through square leg for one. He is off the mark.
Very full this time, Buttler strokes it to mid on.
Good ball again! Flatter and outside off, this one too turns back in. Buttler looks to flick but misses to get hit high on the pads.
Good follow-up delivery after the wicket ball. This is floated outside off, it turns back in sharply. Buttler lets it be.
Birthday boy, Jos Buttler is the next man in for England.

OUT! Finally, finally, Nathan Lyon gets a wicket. It is of the well set Denly and England now have half the side back in the hut. Denly once again falls shortly after getting to his half ton. This is an excellent delivery though. Turn, bounce, it had everything. It lands outside off and spins back in sharply. There is a lot of bounce on it. Denly goes back and tries to defend but the ball hits the handle and lobs towards short leg where Labuschagne takes a dolly. Early wicket for Australia after the break. Also, the visitors will hope, that wicket works wonders for Lyon.
On middle, it is worked through square leg for one.
OHHH! One more length ball around off, this one pitches and comes back in. Denly looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
One more short ball on middle, Denly ducks under it again.
A sharp bumper, Denly ducks under it.
One more back of a length ball on middle, Denly stays back and keeps it out.
Back of a length and on off, Joe defends it out.
Fuller and on middle, it is hit back to the bowler.
On the pads this time, nudged towards fine leg by Jonny.

Just short of the short leg fielder. That shoot off the surface after pitching. Bairstow wanted to work it fine down the leg side but extra bounce means he tries to fend off towards the leg side. It lobs but falls just short of Marnus Labuschagne at short leg.
Flatter one on off this time, another solid block from Bairstow.
Goes full and straight this time, blocked easily.
Fuller around off. Lyon aiming to rough outside off of the batsman. But this is too wide.
Floated around off, pushed towards point by Jonny.
Good nut to end! Just outside off, Denly is not sure whether to play at it or not. He tries to leave it in the end but it goes off the bottom part towards gully.
OHHH! Back of a length and on off, Denly looks to play it late but gets a bottom edge onto the pads.
Shorter and on the body, does not bounce a lot. Denly looks to duck but is hit on the body.
Back of a length on off, it is guided to point.

FOUR! Fifty for Denly! Excellent innings from him. He gets there with a delightful stroke. He creams this full delivery on off through mid off and it races away. He needs to make it big here, he just can't relax. It is his third in Tests.
Fullish and on off, Denly strokes it to mid off.
A little too straight again, Bairstow clips it to short leg.
On middle, it is worked to mid-wicket.
On middle and it is too short. Denly works it through square leg for one.
Very full on off, it is worked to mid on.
Denly comes down the track and works it to short fine leg for no runs.
On middle and turning away. Denly looks to flick but misses.
Nathan Lyon to share the attack with Cummins post Lunch. He is still in search of his first wicket of the match.
One more ball outside off, it is left alone. A maiden to begin with by Cummins.
Outside off, the batter does not play at it.
Very full around off, Bairstow strokes it to mid off.
Another good ball! This is on off and it comes back in again. Bairstow looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Goes very full and on middle, it is hit down to mid on.
Good start for Cummins! On a length and around off, it comes back in. JB looks to defend but misses to get hit near the stomach.

The Aussie players are out in the middle for the second session. Joe Denly and Jonny Bairstow walk out to the middle as well with a daunting task in front of them. Pat Cummins to start proceedings for the visitors post Lunch.
... Day 5, Session 2 ...

Coming to the second session, England would want to continue battling out in the middle while the visitors would want to finish this off as soon as possible to make sure that the Urn stays with them. Join us back for the second session to catch all the action.

For the visitors, it is all about one man at the moment, Pat Cummins. He took two yesterday and has two today. However, Hazlewood too is bowling well but not having the luck. Lyon is getting purchase but is not being able to hit the right lines and lengths. Starc hasn't had a lot to do as of now but he would surely have a part to play.

Australia's session in the end but it was hard work for them. England's overnight batters, Joe Denly and Jason Roy did well to negotiate the first hour of the session but Australia's bowling spearhead Pat Cummins returned for his second spell and castled Roy to end his resistance. Then came the massive moment. Stokes edged one behind and walked. We don't get to see that very often these days. He walked and with him, England's chances of staying in the game has taken a massive dive. However, Denly continues to battle out in the middle. He is nearing his half ton but he needs to make it big here and get able support from the batters coming in too.
Denly survives but by just! Hazlewood lands this just outside off, it is bowled from wide of the crease so Denly plays at it. He is beaten as he does inside the line. LUNCH ON DAY 5!
Nicely left! Just outside off, Denly shuffles across and shoulders arms to this one.
On middle, Denly pushes it to mid on.
That came back in a long way again! This lands outside off and jags back in. The length is shorter. Denly misses his shot and gets hit high on the thigh pad.
One more length ball on middle, Denly defends it off the back foot.
Almost another one! This is on a length and around off, it stays very low. Denly gets his bat down in time and keeps it out.
An away swinger outside off, it is left alone.
Bairstow is off the mark! He works it behind square and collects two.
Shortish and on off, Jonny punches it to covers.
On middle, it is pushed to mid on. It is a NO BALL as Cummins has overstepped.
Outside off, it is left alone.
A short one on middle, JB ducks under it.
Back of a length on off, Bairstow guides it to point.
Bumper to end the over. Denly sways away from it.
FOUR! Fuller ball on off, driven through covers nicely for a boundary. Denly moves to 48 with that one.

Beaten! What a jaffa! Huge appeal as well but not given. Hazlewood pitches this around off, it tails back in to beat Denly's bat and go to Pant behind the wicket. They appeal but not given. Australia do not take the review. The Ball Tracker arrives to and shows that the impact was umpire's call. No inside edge either so can't be caught behind. A good decision from the umpire.
Good length on off, tapped towards gully this time.
In the channel this time, Denly covers his stumps and lets it go to the keeper.
On middle stump on a good length, Denly whips it firmly through mid-wicket for a couple.
Josh Hazlewood is back!
End of a successful over. On off, it is kept out.
On the pads, it is worked to mid-wicket.

FOUR LEG BYES! This is on off again and it jags back in. Bairstow looks to defend but the ball hits the higher part of the back pad and goes between first slip and the keeper and down to the third man fence. There is an appeal from the players but nothing from the umpire.
Back of a length and on off, this is kept out.
Jonny Bairstow is the next man in for England.

OUT! Stokes walks! He is caught behind! This is a massive, massive wicket. Probably the biggest of them all as Stokes has been the man for England. Excellent sportsmanship by him though. Not many in modern day cricket walk but he does here and that too in a game which means so much. Brilliant. Brilliant by Cummins too. He is once again the man doing it for Australia. This is shortish and on off, Stokes initially looks to defend but then tries to leave it on length. Too late by then though as the ball hits the bottom part of the inside edge and goes to the right of Paine. He takes it with a dive and appeals, it is a very confident one. The umpire is unmoved but what do we see? Stokes walks. Australia are ecstatic. England in trouble now. Australia just 6 wickets away. They would hope to take another before Lunch. A rare failure for Stokes.
Shorter and around middle, it is angled away. Stokes leaves it alone.
A single to end the over! This is on the pads, it is worked through square leg for one.
On middle, it is kept out.
That must have hurt! Shorter and on off, Stokes goes back and pushes it but the ball hits the man at silly point.
Loopy ball and on off, Stokes pushes it to mid off.
Almost! Stokes misread the length there. He goes back to a delivery which he should be forward too. gets his bat down though and keeps it out.
On middle, blocked.
Fuller and on off, Denly drives it to mid off.
Shortish and outside off, Denly looks to punch it through covers but is early in the shot. It goes off the inner half towards mid-wicket.
This is angled into the batter, Denly goes right back and keeps it out.
Shorter and on off, Joe pushes it to mid off.
BEATEN! Cummins goes wide of the crease and angles it just outside off. Denly plays inside the line and gets beaten.
Outside off, it is left alone.
On middle, this time, Stokes gets behind the line of the ball and blunts it onto the pitch.
On the pads, it is worked to mid-wicket.
Quicker and on middle, Stokes blocks it easily.
Sharp turn and bounce! Flatter and outside off, the ball pitches, spins away and also bounces. Stokes looks to defend but is beaten.
On middle, Stokes gets right behind the line and defends it again.
Floats it up on middle, Stokes keeps it out.
Nicely guided! This is just outside off, Denly opens the face of the bat and guides it through backward point for two.

LUCKY FOUR! This is just outside off, Denly is not sure whether to play at it or leave it. In the end he tries to leave but the ball hits the bat which is at an angle. Goes past the diving third slip fielder and into the third man fence.
Changes it up now and bangs it short on the body, Denly ducks under it.
Goes extremely full and it is tailing back in from outside off. Denly jams it out.
Good length again and on off, Denly pushes it to mid off.
Ouch! Another good ball. This ball is shaping in nastily. It comes back from outside off and that too after landing. Denly fails to put bat and ball and is hit near the box.
Flighted ball on middle, blocked off the front foot this time.
Another one around off, Stokes blocks it off the back foot.
On off and kept low. Stokes does well to block it towards the off side.
The batsman works it down the leg side. One run added to the total.

Dropped! A chance goes begging there! A beauty from Lyon as he pitches this again on rough. Denly looks to block but gets an inside edge onto the pads. The ball lobs high towards Paine's right who can't hold on. It goes towards fine leg for a run eventually.
Shorter one around off, this kept low. Pushed towards bowler.
Ben Stokes is the new man in. He played an innings of his life in the last game coming in with his team being in similar situation. Can he bail them out, again.

OUT! KABOOM! There's the breakthrough Australia needed. Cummins has provided it. They had to wait for quite a while today for the first wicket but they have now got it. Australia will hope this opens the floodgates. Once again we see the ball sneaking through Roy's bat and pad. Cummins bowls it just outside off and on a length. Roy lunges and tries to push at it but leaves a gap between bat and pad. The ball tails back in, goes between the gap and hits the stumps behind. Also, credit to Paine for the last minute change. Starc was ready to bowl but in the end, he got Cummins on and that has worked wonders. Roy walks back after getting off to a start.
In the channel outside off, left alone by Roy this time.
Fuller ball around off, Denly goes for a drive this time but gets an inside edge the ball goes towards fine leg. He gets a run.
Fuller ball on the pads, Denly looks to flick but is hit on the pads.
Good leave this form Denly. He trusts the length of the ball there. Pitched around off, comes into the batter who shoulders arms and sees the ball go over the timbers.
Fuller ball outside off to start with. Denly finds extra cover fielder to his firm drive.
Starc was ready to but last minute change of thought brings Cummins back into the attack. 6-2-13-2, his numbers so far.

Overthrows! Denly uses his feet and hits it to the right of Cummins at mid on. The batters take a quick run. Cummins fires it at the keeper's end but it is a wild one. No one backing up and hence, the fielder from slip hares after it and saves a run for his side.
Another loud shot but nothing! This is floated outside off, Denly pads it away with his bat behind the pad. An appeal but the umpire feels a shot is offered and he shakes his head.
Shorter and on off, Denly whips it with the turn through mid-wicket for two.
Another tossed up ball on off, Denly keeps it out.
Uses his feet again but once again does not get to the pitch of it. Looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads. An ambitious appeal from the bowler but nothing from the umpire.
Denly comes down the pitch, he does not get to the pitch of the ball so defends it.
Good fielding! This is fuller and on off, Roy strokes it towards mid off. Cummins runs to his right and dives to push it to his right. Mid on then does the mopping up job. The batters take two.
That was close! A yorker just outside off, Roy is late in bringing his bat down and the ball just about kisses the off pole.
Another one on a length and outside off, it is left alone.
Another one on a length and outside off, Roy pushes it to covers.
Closer to the off pole this time, Roy pushes it to covers.
Lands it just outside off, Roy shoulders arms to this one.
On the pads, guided towards fine leg by Denly.
Floated ball on middle this time, Roy comes down the track to work it towards mid on for a run.

And another one lands on the rough outside off and keeps low. Roy looks to block but misses to get hit on the back pad. Lyon appeals but nothing from the umpire. The Ball Tracker rolls in and confirms that the umpire was right. The impact was outside off and was clipping the stumps which means it would've been umpire's call on hitting the wicket. A good call from the umpire.
Another loopy ball on off, Roy blocks it nicely this time.
Another fuller ball which lands on the rough and bounces high into the mitts of Paine.
Floated fuller ball on middle, pushed towards mid on for a single by Denly.

DRINKS! Joe Denly and Jason Roy have negotiated the first hour of the first session well. They weathered the initial storm from Hazlewood and Cummins but they are looking solid now. Australia would want to break this stand as early as they could. They had a couple of chances but the rub of the green seems to be with England at the moment. Interesting hour of play awaits.
Another fuller ball. Roy pushes it towards cover.
Bowls this one on a slightly fullish length on middle. Roy is solid in defense this time.
Squared up on that one. Starc pitches this on off and makes it jag away from Roy's defense and beat the outside edge.
FOUR! Crunched through covers. Starc overpitches outside off, Roy leans into the drive and creams it through covers.
Length ball around off, Roy walks across, blocked.
Shortish length on the body from round the wicket. Denly taps it towards mid on for a quick run.
On off, Roy gets behind the line and keeps it out.
Outside off, it is left alone.

Nicely played! 50 up for England a loud cheer by the crowd. The 50-run stand is also up, a vital one as England were 0 for 2 when the two joined association. Need to keep going. Roy pushes this nicely through covers and takes two.
The batsman defends it from within the crease.
Very wide outside off, it is a full toss. Roy drives it square to point.
Extremely full outside off, Roy pushes it to mid off.
Good running! This is on middle, Roy taps it towards mid on and takes one quickly.
Gets one in the gap! Not right off the middle but enough to get three. Shorter and outside off, Denly slaps it through covers and takes one short of four.
On the fuller side and outside off, Denly goes after it again but finds cover.
Shortens his length a little and lands on middle, defended.

Goa Rocks - 'Me thinks that England are going for the win. Otherwise, why would they play shots like these?' @GR - Ummm... too early to say anything right now. One would feel that looking at the target is not the right way to approach the day. Go for it hour by hour and then session by session and then see post Tea where you stand. Regarding the strokes, it could be to try and put Nathan Lyon off. Remember, he has been struggling in the last 4 innings with the ball. So A. Play strokes to get Lyon off. B. By playing strokes, ensure that one does not get into a defensive mode as happened in the first Test.
A solid drive but for no runs! Fuller and outside off, Denly hits it hard but to covers.

OHHH! Australia making things happen now. A short one by Starc on the body. Denly may have been expecting a full one. He tries to fend it awkwardly but it goes off the handle and lands safe on the off side.
Very full outside off, Roy opens the face and guides it to point. An action-packed over by lyon comes to an end.

Just short now! Once again a heart in the mouth moment, this time for Denly. He brings out the sweep again but hits it uppishly towards deep mid-wicket. The fielder there runs in and then slides to take it but the ball lands short of him. Good stop in the end, saves three.
Quicker and on off, it is blocked.

In the air... safe! Heart in the mouth moment for Roy there. This is floated up outside off, it turns back in sharply. Roy looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads. It lobs over short leg and towards mid-wicket for one.
Shorter and outside off, it turns back in. Roy works it with soft hands towards the leg side.
Nice use of the feet from Denly and works it with the turn through mid-wicket for one.
On a length, closer to off pole, Roy looks to block but it goes off the inner half of his bat towards mid on.

FOUR! That's done nicely by Roy. Another attempt of bowling the yorker has gone wrong as Starc sends a full toss on the pads. Roy whips it firmly through the diving mid on fielder. The fielder gets up and chases but the ball wins the race.
On the pads this time, Denly tucks it towards fine leg off the back foot to take a run.
Good length ball outside off again. Denly has room to slash this through point but he mistimes the shot towards gully.
Outside off this time, Denly lets it go to the keeper.
Good ball and equally well played. Starc is targeting the stumps. He looks to bowl a yorker but dishes out a full toss on middle. Denly blocks solidly.
A tossed up ball on off to end, Denly defends it out.
One more sweep shot, this time to the fielder at deep mid-wicket so just a run.
Loopy ball on off, it is worked with the turn to mid on.
FOUR! That is a top sweep shot. A shot which Denly looks really confident while playing. He drags it from outside off and gets it through square leg.
Another tossed up ball outside off, Denly lunges to defend but the ball turns back in, it goes off the inside edge and onto the pads and lobs safe on the off side.
Flighted outside off, Denly pads it away.
Spin time as Nathan Lyon is on now. He hasn't had a great game and he would love to change that in this innings.
A single to end! Denly pushes this towards cover and gets to the other end.

FOUR! EDGY! Lucky there was Denly. Not a good shot that. Denly is sucked into going after a wide delivery outside off. The ball flies off the outside edge over third slip. Marnus Labuschagne does not react in time and it goes over him and to the third man fence. That went really quickly.
Outside off, left alone.
Gets it right this time and lands it on off and on a length. Denly keeps it out.
On the pads, Denly looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.
Starts with a fuller ball on the pads, Roy flicks it towards square leg for a run.
Mitchell Starc is on now! He seemed to find his rhythm towards the end of the second innings. If he can bowl well here, he could win Australia the game.
On middle, the batter pushes it to mid on.
This is on middle, it is worked down to fine leg for one.
Almost! Just as a write that, Roy plays one out awkwardly. This comes back in after landing on off, Roy looks to put bat on ball but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Down the leg side, Roy looks to flick but misses.
On off, it is kept out again. This is a good start for England, both the batters are looking solid.
One more ball on a length and on off, Roy pushes it to mid off.
A solid block from Denly to finish the over. A good length ball on off from Hazlewood. Denly gets behind the line and blocks it towards the off side.
Back of a length ball this time. Denly ducks under it.
Fuller ball on middle, Roy pushes this towards mid on and takes a run.
Bumper this time but this one goes down the leg side. Roy ducks under it.
Beaten with a beauty! On a length and jags back in. Roy looks to push with hard hands but the ball sneaks in between bat and pad. Wasn't too high from the stumps either.
Length ball on off, blocked by Roy easily.
Well, Cummins to continue!
A short one, Denly spots it early and ducks under it.
On the pads, it is worked down to fine leg for one.
Mitchell Starc is warming up. Does that mean shorter spells for the bowlers?
Shorter again, it comes slow off the surface. Roy gets right behind the line and defends it.
Outside off, Roy watches the ball nicely and lets it be.
A little too straight, Roy fails to put bat on ball and gets hit high on the pads.
Back of a length and it is coming back in. Roy defends it onto the ground.
Another solid push! On off, Denly pushes it towards covers but for no runs.
One more length ball on off, Denly is solid in defense.
Goes back to bowling length on off, it is blocked solidly.
On the fuller side and on middle, Denly strokes it nicely to mid on.

Another loud appeal and a long one but nothing from the umpire! This is on middle and it jags back in. Denly fails to put bat on ball and is hit on the front pad. An appeal but not given. Paine signals it is going down leg.
Just short! Pushing at a delivery Denly need not do. This is behind a length and outside off, Denly looks to stroke it on the up but then stops midway. He ends up chipping it just short of mid off.
Fuller ball on off for Roy. He pushes it back to the bowler.
Hezlewood continues bowling the perfect line and length to the right-hander. This is closer to Denly's off pole. He taps it towards cover and takes off for a quick run. First run for him.
Another ball in the channel on a good length, this time Denly lets it go to the keeper.
Good length ball again on off, blocked nicely this time.
Beaten! A muted appeal follows but dies down quickly. A peach from Hazlewood. Good length in the channel outside off, the ball shapes away from the push of Denly to beat the outside edge.
Good length ball closer to the off pole. Denly lunges forward and blocks.
A length delivery to end on middle, Roy pushes it to mid on.
Outside off, this is left alone.
Goes back to bowling length on off, Roy gets right behind the line and keeps it out.
In the air but wide! FOUR! First boundary and runs of Day 5.  This is angled into the pads, Roy flicks it uppishly but wide of the diving mid-wicket fielder and bags a boundary.
That is a beauty! This is angled into the batter from wide of the crease which means Roy has to play at it. The ball straightens and beats the outside edge of the bat.
On a length and around off, Roy keeps it out.
Pat Cummins to bowl from the other end.
Good length ball outside off this time. Denly watches it shape in and go to the keeper. A tight start from Hazlewood first up.
On the middle pole, Denly gets right behind the line and keeps it out.
One more good ball! Just outside off and it is shorter. Denly leaves it nicely.

A loud appeal but that seems to be going down leg! Once again Hazlewood gets it to tail back in, this time it is fuller but a touch straighter. Denly looks to drive but misses to get hit on the pads. Ball Tracker confirms it is going down leg.
Gets it right this time and bowls it outside off, it tails back in but not enough to make the batter play.
Starts off with a full ball and on middle, Denly pushes it to mid on. A huge cheer for him as he played it nicely. That is how it is going to be today, England fans will be right behind their team.
The Australian players are out in the middle. Joe Denly and Jason Roy are out as well for the hosts to battle out the day. Josh Hazlewood to start the proceedings for the visitors. Here we go...

The equation could not have been any easier to understand, England need to bat out the day if they want to keep their hopes alive of regaining the Ashes. Australia, need 8 wickets if before Stumps if they are to retain the Ashes. There is also a third scenario where the English can score the remaining 365 runs and take a 2-1 lead but that seems improbable. We can surely expect an excellent day of Test cricket. The first session is a very crucial one so stay tuned for it. Welcome to the coverage.
... Day 5, Session 1 ...

England have a lot to ponder once again! Just like most of the times in this Ashes, they have their backs to the wall. Another excellent effort will be needed from them if they are to save this Test. Save is what I write as chasing this down looks improbable. They were in a similar position in the first Test too where they had one day to bat out to save the game and they could not do so. They went down without a fight there, will the same thing happen? We will have to find out. Join us for Day 5 at 1100 local (1000 GMT). Till then, take care goodbye!

Michael Holding is down with Pat Cummins for an interview. He congratulates him for his bowling effort. Cummins says that the ball was coming out of the hand nicely. Further adds he tried to bowl nice and full. He praises Smith's effort and says that he was unbelievable in the middle. On asked about what made them throw the second new ball to him, he says that they wanted to bowl at the stumps and that was their plan. Holding asks Cummins about his workload as Cummins has played all the four Tests. Cummins replies that first he will give the final push for the win on Day 5 and hopes that he will be all right for the final Test as well.

It has been a picture-perfect day for them! They started off by taking the remaining five English  wickets quickly and then courtesy of Smith and Wade, Australia scored another 186 runs to add to the 196-run lead they got. They were eager to get at least a wicket in the final passage of play and they have got two, that too of Root and Burns who were excellent in the first innings. The Aussies could not have asked for anything better.

What a day for Australia! Looking at how things stand at the moment, you would probably say the Aussies will retain the Ashes on Day 5! They have 98 overs on Sunday and all they need to bowl is 8 wicket-taking deliveries and you can bet that their bowlers can do so.
No he can not as he bowls a wasteful of a delivery. He goes for the bumper but bowls it way down the leg side. Roy lets it go to the keeper. THAT WILL BE STUMPS ON DAY 4.

He looks for another yorker but this one is not the perfect one. It is a overpitched ball, Denly leans into the drive to cream it through. However, it doesn't have the legs to reach the fence. They take three before the cover fielder chase and return the ball. 1 more ball to go. Can Starc do something?
Nah. Dishes out a yorker does Starc. This swung in the air. Denly does well to bring his bat down and jam it away.
Another fuller ball, again wide outside off. No swing on offer for him. Denly watches it go back to the keeper again. A bumper now?
Fuller again but too wide to make Denly play at it. He doesn't wanna chase these at this moment in time.
Fuller ball on off, pushed towards point by Denly.
Starc into the attack. This could be the final over of the day.
A single as this is worked through square leg.
On middle, this is worked to mid on.

OHHH! That was close! Picked the wrong ball to sweep there. This is tossed up outside off, it is too full. Denly looks to sweep again but misses. It just misses the off pole. The positive approach is right but you need to pick the right balls.
On middle, it is kept out.
FOUR! That is a top shot. Minimal risk as it was with the turn and it was nicely hit. Stretches out and plays the sweep shot. Drags it outside off and hits it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
On off, Denly works it to mid-wicket.
Well, we have our answer! Nathan Lyon it is as he comes onto bowl now.
A dot to end! This is on middle again, Roy works it to mid-wicket.
Ha ha ha.... Interesting. 8 minutes left. Will Paine go to Starc or Lyon? Starc is warming up but looks like Paine is more interested in Lyon's direction!
This is angled into the pads, Roy gets it past short leg this time and takes an easy two.
One more ball outside off, Roy lets it be.

Ricky Ponting and Nasser Hussain dissect Australia's plan to Joe Root. Normally, Aussies target the opposition skipper and once again, they have been bang on. The key here is the length. Somewhere between full and good, just outside off. In this match, first innings, outside off, nipping back in, LBW. Second innings, slight nip away, hit the top of off. 3 ducks in the last 5 innings for the skipper.
Outside off, it is left alone.
Good work from Wade! This is on middle, Roy looks to defend but it goes off the inner half towards short leg where Wade shows good reflexes and stops it.
A little too short this time, Roy stands tall and pushes it to mid off.
Short and on middle, Denly ducks under it.
One more ball on a good length and around off, it is guided towards point.
Corrects his line and bowls it outside off, it is left alone.
A little too straight once again, Denly tries to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.
A little too straight, Denly works it behind square on the leg side for two.
On the fuller side, no swing on offer for the bowler. Denly plants his front foot forward and strokes it to mid off.

FOUR! First boundary of the chase! This is easy for Roy. A half volley on the pads, it is worked through mid-wicket and the ball races away. Maybe Cummins was guilty of trying a little too hard and hence, ends up bowling a boundary delivery.
A crisp drive! Fuller and on off, Roy strokes it nicely but to mid off.
Roy is really watching the ball closely here. This is shorter and on off, Roy goes back and keeps it out solidly.
On middle and on a length. Roy gets right behind the line and keeps it out.

Wonder what is the reason behind Joe Root coming in at number 3. With 20 minutes to the close, surely a night watchman should have been sent? Craig Overton is seen in his whites in the dressing room, padded up. Ponting asks Nasser Hussain on air whether there is any specific rule in the England dressing room regarding the time to send a night watchman. Nasser replies saying that he is unsure about THIS English team but in general, England sends their night watchman if the time left for the close is 25 minutes or less.
England are underway! This is on the pads, Roy works it through square leg for two.
Another good delivery! This is angled into the batter from wide of the crease. It is on a length, pitches and straightens. Roy looks to defend but then drags his bat back.
Fullish ball this time, tapped towards covers this time by Deny. Top over from Hazlewood to compliment the wicket maiden from Cummins.
Beaten this time! Another ball in the channel outside off. Denly can't resist this time and has a poke. The ball goes past the outside edge.
Oops! Shortish ball, Denly goes to block but it rises a bit to hit on the gloves and then on the elbow. Lucky that it didn't went onto the stumps.
Good leave that one. Another good length ball but this is in the channel. Denly covers his stumps to let it go to the keeper.
Same line and length as the last ball, Denly again solid in defense.
Starts with a length ball, closer to the off pole, Denly is right behind the line of the ball to block towards the off side.
Josh Hazlewood to start the proceedings from the other end. He will be trying to pile on the pressure after the fantastic start provided by Cummins.

One more length ball around off, Roy pushes it to mid on. End of a tremendous over. What a start by Cummins. England get no closer to the target they were set to achieve while Australia get a fist of the wickets they needed
Good length and on middle, it is kept out nicely.
Jason Roy is the next man in who will be facing the hat-trick ball.

OUT! TIMBER! That is a peach! This is Pat Cummins, this is Australia at their best. Outstanding start for them! Root bags a first-baller. An absolute beauty! Exactly what a pace bowler is taught - to hit the top of off and Cummins has done that here. He lands this one on a length and around middle, it pitches and straightens. Root is squared up as he tries to defend. The ball goes past the outside edge and hits the off pole. Root can't believe it as he looks back once. He would probably be thinking, that why him? Why did he get such a perfect delivery first up. Pin-drop silence here. A slow walk towards the pavilion as he knows his side is in big, big trouble now.
Skipper Joe Root arrives early in the middle.

OUT! In the air... taken! Could Australia have asked for a better start than this? The ploy to start the bowling with Pat Cummins has worked wonders. Also, it is a big wicket as Burns has been the in-form player for the hosts. This is a soft, soft dismissal. It is a nothing delivery, down the leg side. Burns looks to flick but is early into the shot. A leading edge and it lobs towards Head at extra cover.
On the shorter side again, it is defended.
Shorter in length and on off, Burns guides it to point.
